# Part 3 – Landsat Satellite System

# 4. Landsat Satellite

## 4.1 Introduction

The Landsat program is the world's longest continuously operating Earth observation satellite mission. It is jointly managed by the **National Aeronautics and Space Administration (NASA)** and the **United States Geological Survey (USGS)**. Since the launch of the first Landsat satellite in 1972, the mission has continuously provided high-quality satellite imagery for scientific research, environmental monitoring, agriculture, forestry, geology, urban planning, and climate studies.

Unlike MODIS, which focuses on frequent observations with moderate spatial resolution, Landsat provides significantly higher spatial resolution images that allow detailed visualization of the Earth's surface. This makes Landsat one of the most valuable sources of satellite imagery for land-cover mapping and thermal analysis.

The long historical archive of Landsat images, spanning more than five decades, has enabled researchers to study long-term environmental changes, including deforestation, urban expansion, glacier retreat, drought, desertification, and climate change.

